title: parametric universal heavy duty 20ml syringe extruder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a parametric derivative of richraps famous universal paste extruder.
It was complete redesigned using openSCAD. I wanted to use 20ml instead of 10ml syringes, so an additional gear was needed to get enough torque.
The construction is quite monstrous, but it fits to standard prusa x-carriage. I tried to make all depending on the syringe size, but this was too hard.
So the default values are for 20ml syringes.
If you want to change it to 10ml or 50lm syringes you have to change more than only the syringe radius variable.
I also added base plates, if someone wants to cast it. The syringe extruder successfully printed frost, hazelnut-spread and marzipan. By adding jelly midprint and pouring chocolade over the finished print one can produce printed multimaterial candy. If you want to read more about this, visit: www.ifeelbeta.de Best

title: Geeetech Prusa I3x Z Axis Wobble Fix

description.text:
I modified this design slightly to include a recess for a PTFE bearing plate. Without the plate the bracket is in direct contact with the acrylic structure may wear or have some unwanted friction.

The PTFE I used was from a sheet 1.5mm thick. The bearing plate is 17mm x 17 mm with a 9mm diameter hole through the centre. PTFE sheet is readily available from on-line stores for a few pounds, and has a very low coefficient of friction.

To ensure these brackets fit on the Geeetech Prusa I3x you need to ensure the couplers are lowered as much as they can go, otherwise the bracket screws will foul the couplers before the z axis reaches Z0. You can re-use the screws from the original brass fittings and use left-over nuts from the original kit.

If you loosen the coupler and fit a hex key to the lower grub-screw then drop this down as low as it can go before tightening then it will not foul.

I took the opportunity to also replace the couplers with ones that aren't split and have 2 grub-screws for each shaft - these run a lot truer which eliminates some wobble. I also replaced the sloppy Z-axis 8mm threaded bar with 8mm leadscrews with 1mm lead.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/d6ZaT9jSMEJ

You may need to run a drill bit down through the centre to allow the brass nuts to fit snugly, and use a small file to open up the inside width of the 'jaws' so they slide smoothly over the 8mm rods.

title: OpenForge 2.0 Cut Stone OpenLOCK Triplex Base Customizer

description.text:
This customizer lets you create your own stone openlock triplex bases for openforge. Presently, I generally use this style with Cut-Stone tiles and use the plain bases for tudor tiles.

For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.

OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our:

  • Online catalog and backer site
  • Website
  • Forums (Mostly we use facebook now)
  • Twitter
  • Facebook

There are five factors to consider when selecting a base.

1) The tile size. This will match between the tile and the base, such as 2x2 or 4x2.

2) The tile shape

  • square
  • diagonal
  • curved

3) The base style

  • plain
  • stone
  • ruined

2) What size basis do you want the tiles to be in. There are three choices:

  • 25mm - every square is 25mm on a side. This is compatible with Dwarven Forge. There is no need to scale the tile top with 25mm.
  • inch - every square is 1 inch (25.4 mm). This is compatible with Printable Scenery (OpenLOCK), DragonLOCK and HirstArts. Scale the tile top when you print it by 101.6% in the X and Y axes.
  • wyloch - every square is an inch and a quarter (31.75mm). This is compatible with hero's horde and wyloch tiles. Scale the tile top when you print it by 127% in the X and Y axes.

3) What connection system do you want to use. We offer 4 connectivity options:

  • Magnetic - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile
  • Magnetic + OpenLOCK - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile. Also has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK Triplex - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square, and at the center of each square.
Changelog

description.text:
I believe I have found a way to reduce or maybe eliminate the need for repeated maintenance on the bowden tube that enters the print head on the CR-10 printers. This design utilizing a bowden tube puts significant stress on the tube as the print head moves side to side in the 'X' axis, causing it to be rotated back and forth in the existing self locking strain relief. This rotation slowly wears on the tube and eventually allows it to retract slightly from within the hot end and thus causes filament leaks and clogging. My Testing is still ongoing but to date, (17-Nov-30), along with Capricorn tubing I have not had to rework the nozzle for quite some time now. Seems to be helping but I am sure the success can also be attributed to the new higher heat range tubing. Happy Printing! Cheers!

2017-Oct-25 Just uploaded a revised clamp to fit tighter on the back plate and added a tab to secure the wire loom. Version 2 relieves the strain on the bowden tube, where it enters the print head, even more. Cheers!

Narrow, flattened spiralized pieces rest in printed casings on 3 sides of the hamper stool. The back is printed, flat pieces hot glued together. For best results use PLA/PHA filament or another slightly flexible filament for the top and bottom horizontal parts. I printed all parts at 0.2 resolution and no support for holes. Bottom and top parts - 20% infill, 2 perimeters. Casings - 25% infill, 1 perimeter. Spirals - no infill, 1 perimeter. I did not use support for the spiral open parts.

Post Note 10/29/2017: Removed side spiral open file and uploaded missing side spiral file.

Hamper Stool Design Notes

My goal was to design a functional piece with low to no toxic out-gassing that could serve as both a clothes hamper and a stool. Since I adore spiral printing for its translucency and flexibility, I wanted it to stand out in this piece. I had hardwood dowels and pine leftover from a table I made and used them to provide the structure to support my weight.

The design began without wheels. I added them when I realized I could just roll the hamper over to the washer and dryer instead of coming back and forth to get clothes.

description.text:
Enjoy smooth, cold brewed coffee with this print!

After some experimentation and a few clogged filters, I ended up with this triple filter design based on two 1 quart wide mouth mason jars and progressively smaller filters. The cut-away drawing shows the final system stack-up.

The recipe I am currently using includes 1 cup of coarse ground coffee, 3 cups of cold water
in a mason jar, closed with a wide mouth lid and ring, brewed for 6-12 hrs on the counter. I insert a paper filter, made for basket coffee makers (8-12 cup), in the flat bottom filter section, assemble the system and invert to allow gravity to work its magic. To drink, I heat 1 part brew, one part water and enjoy the result hot, but look forward to trying it over ice next summer.

Please be aware there are challenges to making 3D printed objects food safe. If you haven't already, you might use this as an opportunity to educate yourself.

description.text:
So a few years ago I was getting ready to move and packed up my single cup coffee maker. I really wanted to make some coffee (the stuff at the coffee shops is just too expensive!) so I figured out a way to do it without buying a coffee maker. I used a red plastic bowl and knifed slits in the bottom to hold the coffee and filter and I've been using it ever since. I have a dedicated pan for boiling water so it only needs to be cleaned once in awhile. It's just so much easier. You can't set a timer, but I don't miss it. It's finally starting to break apart so I thought I'd build a design to print out that would replace it and also fix some downfalls of the original (mainly just somewhat slow drainage).
The only issue is what material to use for it. I would recommend using one of taulman's materials that can withstand the heat and is FDA approved (the 618 isn't approved, but I have it and it states it is inert to the body so that's what I'm going to try. Use at your own risk if you use that material. I would not recommend ABS). Update: Printed out and coffee tastes great! I put the strainer in a pot of boiling water and it didn't lose structural integrity. Update: Added strainer for smaller diameter cups

Coffee_strainer - original with curved bottom
Coffee_strainer-2 - original with flat bottom
Coffee_strainer-smaller_cup - modified for smaller diameter cups.
I would recommend using one of taulman's materials that can withstand the heat and is FDA approved (the 618 isn't approved, but I have it and it states it is inert to the body so that's what I'm going to try. Use at your own risk if you use that material. I would not recommend ABS).
This design does require supports except for the bottom and first "step".
If you print the strainer for the smaller diameter cup, make sure infill isn't 100% as there are some thicker portions due to the curvature of the part. I would recommend 20% w/ 2mm thickness. That's just generally what I've found to work good.

title: ELP 720p USB Webcam module enclosure and mount

description.text:
In search of perfect Webcam to use with my 3D printer (via Octoprint) (Logitech C270 is good but it has very narrow field of view) I discovered these awesome ELP USB camera modules. They are small, cheap, have wide lens and work great with Raspberry Pi.

This is complete enclosure and mount "stem" that can be attached to 2020 extrusion frames like one on Creality CR-10. There's also a mount for MakerGear M2 printer.

M2 mount is simply attached to frame corner and uses M3 nut and M3 screw to hold it securely in place.

IMPORTANT NOTE About ELP camera and OctoPi image:
I've discovered that if you are running Octopi (Raspberry Pi image with Octoprint), it will not work with ELP cameras by default. This is due to Octopi distro trying to start camera with 10 frames per second parameter. It looks like ELP cameras do not support that. Fortunately this is easy to fix.

  • Edit /boot/octopi.txt file
  • Find line (it will have hash/pound sign in front of it:
    camera_usb_options="-r 640x480 -f 10"
    Remove has/pound sign (uncomment) and change -f value from 10 to 15, like so:
    camera_usb_options="-r 640x480 -f 15"
  • Reboot

  • Close back piece, orienting cutout for USB cable in correct spot
  • Case is designed to snap it, however depending in your printer it could come out loose. In that case use two optional screws to hold it together. I used 2-28 x 1/4" plastic self tapping screws.

title: Black Ram Hand - MVII (BIG Robot)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This Black Ram Hand was designed to be BIG and used for Robot costumes. It is entirely 3D printable including the bolts and nuts.

50% larger than the size of the Mark V, its can be attached to your arm for a costume as a Robot. It's size really feels huge when on your arm. It works by flexing your wrist allowing the claw to open and close.

Adjust the claw position to change the opening and closing claw size. Use velcro strips to attach to your wrist and forearm.

https://youtu.be/1bxfs37s4Ps

Printer Brand:

Zortrax

Printer:

Zortrax M200

Resolution:

0.14

Notes:

You will need to print:

1 x Robot hand
1 x Robot gauntlet
1 x Robot claw slider
1 x Robot tendon
1 x Robot tri-claw
3 x Robot gripper a
3 x Robot gripper b
3 x Robot gripper c
12 x Robot claw bolt a
12 x Robot claw nut
8 x Robot bolt
4 x Robot nut

I tried to design with clearances between components, however different 3D printers will have different tolerances and output. Try to print on the highest resolution possible to ensure that you will get the proper clearances between parts.

I recommend that you print the bolts and nuts individually (unless your retraction function works well). This will allow for a well formed threads. It may be tedious but you will get a much better result on your assembly. Also the FILL Density should be at least 80% on Bolts and Nuts to make them strong and able to handle tension.

Other parts can have way less infill and adding more can increase the weight of the claws (I got tired holding it up). If you have stronger materials I would only use them on the bolts and nuts. But check the assembly first because they can be very tight which means that I will have to adjust to give more clearance.

Black Ram Hand (Big Robot) in action Design

I designed this arm to really be for a costume or prop compared to the previous versions. I designed it in Creo 3 and spent most of the time focusing on the linkages which create the open and closing claw from the wrist movement.

Socket #1 was the biggest and go down in size order from there. I also included parameters for setting the spacing of the two rows and to compensate for printing differences. While you can tweak these figures for your own, the model is not perfect linked so elements of it could break and require tweaking to work depending on what changes.

Made a mistake snapping your acrylic in a straight line? No problem! just hide it with an elegant trim! As an added bonus, it hides the magnets to hold the door shut.

Designed for 3 mm plexiglass. Each trim is 230 mm long for half my door length, and the magnet position is halfway.

Each side is 3mm because my magnets were 2mm tall, so the door isn't flush to the front surface of the table.

I bought the 10 mm diameter refrigerator magnets from here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0714KZP5C/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I didn't add an extra tolerance to the magnet indent because I didn't want it rattling around. Place a magnet on each side of the hole and use a flat head screw driver to push it in (the other magnet should keep it from moving away). Aligning the magnets to the Lack leg is pretty simple if you leave the magnet on the other side of the trim magnet and close the door.

I didn't bother gluing the trim together or to the plexiglass. Unfortunately the top right corner was slightly exposed.

STEP file included.

description.text: Testing a stand to hold multiple micro USB devices.

Contribute: https://github.com/heyharvs/gelholder

This is a GU Energy gel holder designed in OpenSCAD and completely customizable. Default is 5 gels but customizable up to 12 for you ultra endurance athletes. I saw a similar concept online but is nowhere to be found for purchase, so I decided to improve on the design and make it available for everybody.

Design Highlights
1) uses standard zip ties to mount to front fork for stability
2) slots are designed specifically for GU Energy gels
3) slots are tapered and angled to provide enough support
4) optional but recommended 2nd zip tie slot
5) customizable stem diameters, gel counts, and toggles for logo and second zip tie slot

Adding GUs
1) With only the front ziptie installed, rotate the ladder to the side a bit.
2) Fold one side of the GU gel flap and insert into the top slot first.
3) From the underside of the holder, unfold the flap so it's snug
4) After adding all gels, bend all gels and flaps towards the back of the bike (see pic)
5) Insert a zip tie at the end of the ladder to add extra security
6) Power through your race like a champion...

Update
For convenience, I've added 2 common configurations of 5 and 10 gels which is roughly a 70.3 or 140.6 Ironman distance.

Update 2
Just completed the 2017 Austin Ironman to test out the design. Worked perfectly, just enough tug to keep all the gels firmly in place. A tiny tip though, the GU packets have sharp edges at the bottom corners, so I recommend you clip/round off the edges to avoid hitting your leg while off the saddle.

If you want to scale it up, you will have to modify the finger hinges in a design program to allow them to function, because they won't work as well or at all if they get too thick. eNabling the Future has a good instructional video, just remember that this hand doesn't need elastic. title: AMP plug 3 pole v3 (2 poles used)

description.text:
This thing is a housing for 3x 6.35mm (2 used only) female connectors (plug) often used in many washing machines and other machines made by LG Electronics. Those plugs can be found in similar products with several other brand names as well.
This time the used filter type is Tyco SZ 06021 but you will find a number of similar filters as well.
The plug housing has been simplified to meet my need connecting the power line filter with the controller board or other internal device.

After printing the thing:
Crimp the wires to the two female connectors.
Flatten out the small flexible notches that afix the female connector with the male blade connector (on the board).
Otherwise you will not be able to remove the plug from the controller board later on.
The two used connectors have to be fed in from the front opening instead of the back.
Feed in one wire from the front toward the back side.
Heat up the female connector (clamp) with a torch or heatgun slightly so it can soften the plastic a bit when you have pushed it in , do this the next step.
Drag the wire commeing out of the back opening and push in the femal connector at the same time now.
Having a car lamp H4 pluged into the female connector helps to find the right position.
Adjust the dived in connector until the base of the lamp hits the front of the housing.
Let cool down the connector before removing the helping H4 lamp then.
Repeat the procedure for the other connector.

See the pictures I have added. Warming up not shown.

Remember: it is allways a good practice to fasten the plug using some silicone or hot glue, you know? Don't let it slip away.

Please note : this not a genuine qualified replacement for the stock parts.
If you are unsure about using electronics esp. working with high voltage from the mains, do not repair your appliance.
Ask qualified persons for help.

description.text:
This is a roller I made for 69mm rolling papers (e.g. Zig Zags), that I have since expanded into most conventional paper sizes. It uses m3 screws(8-30mm ) so it is easier to take belts off and on.

Print Rollers vertically

Comments and makes are appreciated

BELTS

Method A:
Currently only 69mm belt pictures
I included some belts with trippy patterns that you can print on a piece of A4 paper.Simply plaster over the belt with clear packing tape. Then cut around the red rectangles leaving a little bit of excess paper on the long sides. Roll up the paper and use a piece of packing tape to tape the two ends together with the bottom of the image overlapping a few mm over the top of the image.

Method B:

Another way to make the belt is out of the the label of a water bottle cut to 90mm-110mm * the length of the paper. Or print out a pattern sheet from method A to use as a template. I recommend taping both the inside and outside of the belt.

Method C:

Do method B but use a zip-lock bag instead.

Method D:

Buy a belt at a headshop. The big downside here is that they are often too small for the rollers.

Other

You should sand down the rollers. You can do this by hand but I found it easier to use a cordless drill. I did this by putting the end of the roller in the chuck of the drill and spinning it while rubbing it with sandpaper. Be careful not to get it too hot or burn yourself, It gets hot very quickly.

For the actual assembly start by screwing in both rollers on one side. Next tilt them upwards still so you can put the belt on. Then slide the belt over the two rollers, you want the belt to be oriented in a way that when you use it normally you aren't rolling against the fold(If the fold catches you have it on wrong). Finish up by simply screwing in the other side.

description.text:
This is a remix of my original found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:239710. That one worked fine but I found that (as always) there were improvements that could be made. Change log:
  • I moved the bowden push fit connector to the back plane to increase range of movement for the lever without adding unneeded bend to the filament, so now there is a cleaner path of travel for the filament with less friction.
  • I added a funnel to the top of the bowden connection area to ease filament changes.
  • I made the transition area between the funnel and the pushfit connector more tailored to remove any chance of snagging there during filament changes
  • I also changed the feed tube on the lever to make it more robust, it was a little thin before
  • I recreated the back plane in openscad and made the lever modification in openscad (I didn't feel like recreating the wheel with the lever, just tinkered with it a bit).
    • As before:
    This can be used wherever a direct drive bowden extruder is desired. With hole for push fit connector. I had problems with all the spring version extruders. Initially they would work but after a few months they would lose compression and start glitching. So I built an extruder loosely based on Joe Chung's remake of Whosawhatsis' minimalist extruder that uses a screw instead of a spring. I still wanted some flex though to allow for the possibility of some filament with low diameter tolerances so I use an M4 screw to apply tension and use about 5-6mm thick piece of rubber cut off from a rubber plug found at the hardware store for $1. In order for the M4 screw not to dig in to the rubber, use an M3 washer between the end of the screw and the rubber. This is designed to work in conjunction with my mounting bracket for a Cerberus (Rostock style) Printer found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:159478 It could also be mounted directly to an aluminum extrusion with appropriately sized T-Slot nuts.

Unless you're going to modify this, you only need the BackSidePlate.stl and the FinishedLever.stl. **Notes
1) Use a 12mm M3 screw to hold a 623 bearing in (M3 self taps)
2) Tap the push-fit connector hole with an M5 screw before screwing in the push-fit. (I like to tap it just a turn or two, then start the insert the pushfit connector a bit, then heat the metal on the pushfit (I use a soldering iron) while carefully finishing to tap/connect the pushfit. When you're done, the pushfit is very well secured in place.)
